{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568366"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:14:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:14:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20037"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20037"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.12,0.07,0.51,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12816"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88512"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12816"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72716"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1889"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2173"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"3426"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"5820"},{"type":"tags","id":"11701"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"30265"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45414"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88512"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of fever, drenching night sweats, severe headache, and generalised muscle and joint pain. He went pig hunting in rural New South Wales two weeks ago and butchered several wild pigs on this trip. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He works as a carpenter and has not travelled overseas recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.4\u00b0C. He has mild hepatosplenomegaly and generalised lymphadenopathy. There is no rash, jaundice or meningism. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 135 g/L (130-180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 6.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 140 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein 85 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine aminotransferase 65 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAspartate aminotransferase 70 U/L (5-40).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tularaemia","Leptospirosis","Bartonellosis","Brucellosis","Q fever"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an undifferentiated febrile illness after exposure to wild pigs in rural New South Wales, consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003EBrucellosis. \u003C/strong\u003EBrucellosis is caused by infection with bacteria of the genus \u003Cem\u003EBrucella\u003C/em\u003E, with \u003Cem\u003EBrucella suis\u003C/em\u003E being the most common species in Australia, particularly associated with feral pigs. The incubation period is typically 1-3 weeks. Clinical features include undulant fever, night sweats, malaise, headache, and musculoskeletal pain, all of which are present in this patient. Hepatosplenomegaly and lymphadenopathy are common findings. The patient\u0027s history of butchering wild pigs provides a clear exposure risk, especially if personal protective equipment such as gloves were not worn at the time as the bacteria can enter through cuts or abrasions in the skin or via mucous membranes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeptospirosis\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by \u003Cem\u003ELeptospira\u003C/em\u003E species and can present with similar symptoms. However, it is more commonly associated with exposure to water or soil contaminated with urine from infected animals, particularly rodents. While it can occur after contact with infected pigs, the clinical picture typically includes more prominent renal and liver involvement, often with jaundice, which is not described in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQ fever\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by \u003Cem\u003ECoxiella burnetii\u003C/em\u003E and is another important zoonotic infection in Australia. It is more commonly associated with exposure to cattle, sheep, and goats rather than pigs. While it can present with fever, headache, and malaise, it often causes a more prominent pneumonitis or hepatitis picture. The absence of respiratory symptoms makes Q fever less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETularaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by \u003Cem\u003EFrancisella tularensis\u003C/em\u003E and is rare in Australia. It typically presents with an ulcer at the site of inoculation and regional lymphadenopathy. The absence of a characteristic ulcer makes tularaemia less likely in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBartonella henselae\u003C/strong\u003E is the causative agent of cat scratch disease. It typically presents with regional lymphadenopathy following a scratch or bite from a cat. While this patient does have lymphadenopathy, the absence of a history of cat exposure and the presence of severe systemic symptoms make \u003Cem\u003EBartonella henselae\u003C/em\u003E infection unlikely. Cat scratch disease typically causes more localised symptoms and lower grade systemic features (malaise and low grade fever) than seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiagnosis of brucellosis is confirmed by blood cultures (which may take up to three weeks to grow) and serological testing. Treatment typically involves a prolonged course (six weeks or more) of combination antibiotics, usually doxycycline plus rifampicin or gentamicin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Brucellosis should be considered in patients with undifferentiated febrile illness and occupational or recreational exposure to animals such as wild pigs in at risk geographic locations.","Brucellosis typically presents with fever, sweats, malaise, headache, and musculoskeletal pain.","Blood cultures and serological testing are the mainstay of diagnosis for brucellosis."],"references":["Mor S, Wiethoelter A, Massey P, Robson J, Wilks K, Hutchinson P. Pigs, pooches and pasteurisation: The changing face of brucellosis in Australia. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2018;47:99-103. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/march/brucellosis","Qureshi KA, Parvez A, Fahmy NA, Abdel Hady BH, Kumar S, Ganguly A, Atiya A, Elhassan GO, Alfadly SO, Parkkila S, Aspatwar A. Brucellosis: epidemiology, pathogenesis, diagnosis and treatment-a comprehensive review. Ann Med. 2023;55(2):2295398. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10769134/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72716"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20037"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72716"},"a